---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Security | BeaconGuard Runtime Admission and Fail-Closed Control"
  description="BeaconGuard provides deterministic request admission, trust and freshness checks, release verification, and fail-closed DENY behavior before governed execution."
>
  <section class="stack-section">
    <h1>Security at the Runtime Control Boundary</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      BeaconGuard admits requests only after deterministic validation against the Active Verified Release. Admission failures return DENY. Evidence supports reconstruction and governance review; it does not replace SIEM, IAM, GRC, or customer security programs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Deterministic request admission</h2>
    <p>
      The Runtime Control Boundary validates and normalizes request context, then evaluates trusted signals against the Active Verified Release. Runtime results are ALLOW or DENY only.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Signature and trust checks</h2>
    <p>
      Required trust signals and signature or integrity expectations for request context must be satisfied before evaluation proceeds. Missing or invalid trust conditions fail closed as DENY.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Freshness and replay checks</h2>
    <p>
      Request identity, timestamps, and freshness windows support replay and freshness detection. Exact nonce, cache, or signed-constraint mechanisms are deployment-dependent. Failed checks return DENY.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Release verification and activation</h2>
    <p>
      Only an Active Verified Release governs runtime evaluation. Distributed releases must pass Release Verification and Activation before use. Mix-and-match or unverified artifacts are outside the approved runtime path.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Fail-closed behavior</h2>
    <p>
      When required controls, approvals, trust signals, freshness conditions, or replay checks are invalid, missing, stale, or out of bounds, BeaconGuard returns DENY and prevents downstream execution. There is no permissive fallback to a review-as-permission state.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>External dependencies and customer responsibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Identity providers and source-system trust remain customer-controlled.</li>
      <li>Replay-state providers, when used, are external to the core decision evaluation and must be configured for fail-closed operation.</li>
      <li>Evidence storage durability and integrity protection depend on the configured evidence provider and customer infrastructure.</li>
      <li>Network, TLS, secrets, and host hardening remain deployment responsibilities.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>What BeaconGuard is not</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Not a replacement for SIEM, IAM, GRC, WAF, or API gateway platforms</li>
      <li>Not a probabilistic authorization engine</li>
      <li>Not a certification or attestation of legal compliance</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="/proof-evidence">Review Proof and Evidence</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/trust-assurance">Trust Center</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/docs/threat-model">Threat Model</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
